Fun facts:¬† * All worker bees are female, hence "Great work, little sister!" They are the ones who have the stingers. * Male bees are drones.  They do not have stingers and thier only purpose is to mate with an unfertilized queen. * Chances are, if you ever wanted to pet a bee, the best time to pet one is when they are polinating - as they are too preoccupied with polination to even care that you are there. * Bees are very unlikely to sting you unless you corner them or are seen as a threat.  Unlike wasps, they don't sting you just to sting you. * Overall, they are very nice creatures and you shouldn't be afraid to greet one if it comes up to you.  Chances are, it's just curious on what you're doing (ie: yard work, washing a car, etc.) and won't sting you.  If you swat at them gently, they won't bother you again; unless you smell nice and sweet (Take it as a compliment from a bee.  A FEMALE BEE LIKES YOU FOR PETE'S SAKE!  XD )

@xFantasy Dreamer No, it's a thing from real life bees.  When a queen bee dies, the workers select a group of about five larva and feed them a secretion the worker bees make from their heads called royal jelly. This jelly triggers certain changes in the larva's body, like the growth of ovaries, increased size, all the differences a queen has. Those five larva will battle it out and the one left standing will be the new queen.  That's what I could recall from memory, a couple things might be off; you should probably look it up too.

Nice, but several corrections. Bees collect the nectar, not the pollen. Collecting pollen is more a thing that just happens without the bees intending to do so. The bees are interested in the nectar of the flowers and the flowers are like "Fine, but could I bother you to take some pollen with your while we are at it?". So the queen bee sending the worker bees out to collect pollen is inaccurate. Second, a bee doesn't die when stinging other insects and animals. It dies when stinging humans. A bee's stinger has hooks on it. The point if to sting another insect and yank their innards out for maximum damage and insta-kill. Therefore, in the insect world, bees are quite deadly. Problem is only that human skin is very flexible and the hooked stinger just gets stuck there. And when the bee instinctively tries to yank our innards out, it accidentally ripps off its own innards because our skin is less likely to tear then their abdomen. Third, yes indeed. Bees use dance moves to communicate where they found the most delicious source of nectar.

@Somebody okay we all know this   something interesting about it though is bees signal to other bees when they spot danger (us) and will attack accordingly to protect their hive. this is why smoke is sometimes used during bee removals. it keeps them from communicating with each other. fun fact: bees know which way is up and which way is down inside their hive, and they use this to show direction. Bees dance with the waggle run at a specific angle away from straight up. Outside the hive, bees look at the position of the sun, and fly at the same angle away from the sun.

A Walk Home Endings  Ending One: The player makes up with their boyfriend, Jonas. The ending can be achieved by walking straight home without taking any pictures and without looking at the man following you. This includes staying away from places like the cave or shack that can be found in the forest. Once the player reaches their house, they should get a text message from Jonas, thanking you for the visit. Upon receiving the text, head out onto the balcony to see Jonas waving at you from below, and complete the first ending. (Good Ending)  Ending Two: In this ending, the player returns home to be confronted by the man that has been following you. Presumably, one of you die in this scenario, although the game ends before we are shown anything. To get this ending, you must find all of the instances where the killer appears. Along with this, you should also take pictures of blood stains, garbage cans, dead animals, sometimes graffiti or posters, and the man. This includes the cave and shack found in the forest. Upon returning home, you should be locked in and placed into the stand-off with the man. (Bad Ending)  Ending Three: To achieve the final ending, you must discover every interactable item in the game. This ending is often spotty with its triggering, and there's slight debate online about the exact steps to trigger it. Generally, it is accepted that you must approach the car to set off the alarm, trigger the jump scare in the shack, photograph the animals, and tip over the scooter by the vista. Once you've completed everything, head to the front of your house and hope that you trigger the "behind you" voice line. Once you hear it, turn around and face the street to see a man get ran over. Head inside your house and achieve ending three. The ending's significance is often debated, although most people think you are caught by the police. (Secret Ending)  Overall, the general consensus is that the player is responsible for the missing animals. The man following you home is actually your boyfriend, Jonas, as he suspects you to be involved with the missing animals; hence the posters found inside his house. This is also implied with the photographs reading "He Knows" once triggering the jump scare in the shack. This ending has holes though, and some people point out the man getting ran over in ending three. As far as I could tell, we don't see any dead people throughout the game, only animals. The man in ending three could be referencing ending two, where you presumably kill Jonas for finding out your secret. However, if the man following you home IS Jonas, then that would mean that HE was the person driving the car we see hitting the man in ending three. We know this because the same car that hits the man in the road can be found in the parking lot shortly before you return home. Coincidentally, the man following you is standing next to it before it drives off frantically, eventually returning to kill the man in the street.   I'm glad Mark got around to playing this game, as it honestly goes a lot deeper than I initially expected. There's still a lot of things that I'm curious about, such as what the true ending really suggests or some of the odd graffiti sprayed on the wall that might imply something deeper. Also, I did notice the 'thunder' that you can hear in Mark's gameplay when he returns to the house. As far as I can tell, this sound effect hasn't played very often or maybe even at all. (Watching again I realize this could be thunder being picked up from Mark's microphone, and might not actually be in the game.) I may be thinking too deep, but I am curious if there is still something hidden within the game that no-one has found yet, even though we've discovered all of the endings. I'd love to see Mark revisit this game to achieve all the endings and maybe start to fall down the same rabbit hole I did while researching the topic. Thanks for the read, guys.

@Roobun as someone who is neurodivergent myself, the way i see it is that disability is a neutral word. it simply means society is not built for people with conditions like ours. for example, sensory issues are disabling because they can inhibit someone from living daily life in the same way as a neurotypical. but their life is still a good life!! disability is a useful term because it highlights the ways in which society is hindering people like us. if society changes and we have the same rate of success and happiness as neurotypicals did, then we wouldn‚Äôt be disabled!! but because there are obstacles in society which make our life difficult in more ways that one, it‚Äôs a disability. hope that makes sense :) don‚Äôt let negative views of neurotypicals keep us from using language to define our experiences!! i also think it‚Äôs up to the individual to define their experience. if mark didn‚Äôt feel disabled by his condition then i wouldn‚Äôt refer to him that way again. but he could also feel that it is disabling (as a lot of ppl with adhd do) and he should be able to identify that way as well. people should use labels they feel comfy with and others should respect that :)

So he wrote a speech, used a bunch of fancy words and blew these kids minds because they didnt know what the fuck he was saying, assumed he was smart and made him Judge for the day.  Well. My husband made the position corrupt. Because he controlled the police, he allowed himself to be exempt from all of the "laws" which were very simple like, don't step on the grass. One of the news journalists noticed this and wrote an article about him being corrupt.  My husband created new laws about creating false information and since he was never charged with anything, he deemed the article to be false and had his police arrest the journalist kid, and since they weren't allowed to mess with the laws on the board, the kid had no idea what he was being charged with (my husband just had a bunch of rules made up in his mind so he just went around getting people arrested and they had no idea why) he also told the police to be rough with him and they ended up pushing him into the grass so the kid got called out on that. As someone who struggles with deep depression, the secret ending makes sense to me. The mc worked hard, and deserves rest. Pushing himself all the way can be counterproductive, and fresh air is metaphorical rather than literal. He didn‚Äôt need to go outside when he felt so incredibly anxious about it, he improved his mind and made it feel safe. He felt a moment of relaxation. When every day is a struggle, a day of self-care is a step in the right direction.

And truly, sometimes when you do everything right, and you go outside, and you get your fresh air, you‚Äôll go home and feel the exact same. Everyone told you going outside and getting fresh air will make you feel better. But it didn‚Äôt. Why didn‚Äôt it? Must be something wrong with you.    There‚Äôs nothing wrong. Fresh air can help in other situations, but trust your gut and ignore the voices. If you truly feel like rest will help you, it will. Especially when you‚Äôve been using it as coping for so long, turning it into a reward is even better.

As someone who has had extreme depression in the past before. I have a theory that going outside is a metaphor for suicide. Sometimes you think you want to leave everything behind, but what your really need to do is to acknowledge what you have done, accept how far you have come, and be content with that.

@Austin Lucas I don't read it that way. I mean, yes, it's true that the shelf still isn't fixed. But there are also a lot of dangers in that house that aren't fixed: he can't fix it all in one day. He could barely move some boxes and organize some papers.  Idk, depression is like that. Sometimes you can't work on the really pressing things.... you can see when he tries, he gets overwhelmed, and "dies" (like the bee death). But if you work on the little things, and build your distress tolerance... eventually the bigger things, won't seem so big anymore.  It probably took a long time for his house to get into that state... and it'll take a long time to get it fixed, too. The important thing, is that he's doing maintenance. Even if the maintenance seems unintuitive, and his living situation is still dangerous.
i also think ! that maybe it's saying that going outside won't magically solve your problems , and that sometimes , you just have to take care of your brain before outside becomes an option

To me this game shows how difficult simple tasks can be when living with depression.   Washing your face, brushing your teeth, brushing your hair, taking care of your environment, eating etc ‚Ä¶ are hard to accomplish because of all the work and energy you have to put in to be able to accomplish those tasks.   Not only that but the narrator in the game is the depressive thoughts, squeezing the energy and motivation out of you.   Going outside is terrifying as well because your little space no matter how dirty, worn down or ugly it can be, it‚Äôs still a safe space where you can rest, not care about the outside world, not care about your responsibilities, you don‚Äôt work yourself to exhaustion trying to live a life, you just let your illness eat you alive and sometimes that can be more comforting than trying to get any better.   All of the framed photos, documents, toys and various forgotten memories kind of represent self isolation. Forgetting about your family, friends and social life. Your childhood toys are in a basement completely forgotten because they‚Äôre is no joy in remembering them.   Basically the whole game to me can be about the ¬´¬†but just do it¬†¬ª thing, where people don‚Äôt necessarily understand how difficult simple songs can be living with depression.

@Ultima DoombotMK1 shit   That's the point. There is no real way out of chronic depression, you can't win against your own physical brain. The goal is to just keep going and improve what you can. @marcello deltoro that's mental illness. You can't just make it through one or two days and then you'll be fine. That's not how it works. Yeah, it sucks ass--and yeah, it's bull shit, but that's just how it is sometimes. You just make it though each day the best you can. Sometimes tomorrow is better, sometimes it's not. I think going to sleep was the best for the secret ending. I agree with what Mark says though, growing complacent with small victories isn't a good thing.  However, the MC was clearly a person at the start of their journey. They weren't on the tail ends of dealing with their depression - quite the opposite - they hadn't eaten, washed or even gotten out of bed in days. They were definitely just starting to take their first steps to caring for themselves.  Going outside is the end goal. The thing you work towards above all else. It's not something you do in a day.  They completed so many milestones that day and it exhausted them because it was so much all at once but they still deserve to be happy with themself because they managed to complete some self-care tasks.  They didn't clean their house or shower but they freshened up, organised a few things and made a comfortable place to rest that _wasn't_ their bed. Baby steps.  The idea of going outside clearly panicked them and most likely would cause a panic attack if they forced themselves to do so, which would just put them back to square one. Who would want to go outside if the only thing they associate the outside world with is stress?  You'll get to that point eventually. It may take a while but it will happen. At some point getting out of bed may get just that little easier or brushing your teeth might become habit and those are the milestones you should be aiming for.  Nothing comes from overwhelming yourself, if you've not gotten out of bed for a while but just got a glass of water, I have a genuine congratulations for you! Keep doing so, maybe in a few months or weeks or even days, that'll become the norm for you and you can press onwards from that <3  Going outside... Fresh air... Your ultimate goal is just that. The endgame. Take your time to get there and as long as you're still moving forwards, no matter how slow, or how many off-days or backwards steps you take, you're doing your best and working so hard. You've got this! <3

other people have given their perspectives on the secret ending, but as someone who struggles with deep depression as well, i think i'm qualified to give my 2 cents :D   the secret ending seems counterintuitive, especially to someone who doesn't struggle with depression and can't exactly understand what we go through; i'm not saying this to sound condescending, it's just difficult to entirely grasp the weight on someone else's shoulders if you haven't personally experienced it.  to me, what this game is saying is that it's okay to take baby steps. our protagonist gets dressed, cleans up, eats some food, organises some papers, and decorates a space just for them outside of their own bed. these are relatively easy tasks for most people, but as we can see at the start of the game (based on the fact none of these tasks are accomplished) that the protagonist struggles deeply with them. i believe it's part of the reason the game has so many convoluted ways to do simple things, like finding a toothbrush behind the socket in the wall in order to brush your teeth, or only being able to see your face in the mirror after a great many other tasks have been completed. these things are hard to do when deep in the throes of depression, as this game and the house we find ourselves in (as mark already pointed out, a clear allegory for the protagonist's mind) makes evident. the game also deals with themes of agoraphobia, specifically leaving the home that they've become so comfortable in; this is dual-pronged, as in it's hard to LITERALLY leave your house when depressed, and also hard to FIGURATIVELY leave the depressive thoughts in your head; how uncomfortable it is to have to face the anxieties and fears you've been willfully suppressing and how panic-inducing it can be, which is what the red light outside the door and in other tense situations seems to symbolise.   eventually, yes, you'll have to. but sometimes, it's enough to take small steps towards a greater goal. our protagonist has already accomplished so much, and they do get some well-deserved fresh air at the end of the game. maybe not literal fresh air, but a bit of peace of mind is a kind of fresh air in itself, is it not? <3

@KopyKat I really believe there are hazards that will stop us on both sides. The need to not be satisfied with minimal effort is a real thing. ...But at the same time, never being satisfied with keeping "enough for today" small? It mostly just sounds like a guilt trip, and it's an echo of the same voice of cynicism that nothing will ever be enough.  Personally, when I hear that from anywhere - people I know, people I don't know (like you), even the parts of my own mind that repeat that I'll never get anywhere at this rate... I get angry. They don't get it, and I don't think you get it. Yes, you have to push yourself, but you also have to be able to stop pushing and rest and be rewarded or the pushing Will Just Break You. And yes, sometimes even "this little" needs to be enough. It's not so little anyway... In order to have the fully decorated area and unlock the secret ending, the protag has to have fairly deeply explored their mind, sorted out their living space, corrected a bunch of crap which was left in really stupid places in order to even find their self-care stuff again, folded away a bunch of boxes, organized a bunch of paperwork, and then done the actual decorating, while avoiding distractions and being overwhelmed by ideations along the way. You don't *get* the secret ending by only doing basic self-care, it took reaching a milestone of Sorting Out The Crap. That is more than a holding pattern. You can't *do* that with evasive minimal-effort.

Bipolar misdiagnosed chronic depression ten years ago.   I disagree to a extent. Mark is right. You have to push and it will feel like too much.   You and many others say it's good but that's a trap. You will get stuck in the small things being enough. Depression will use that thought to convince you to stop at those small things because they are so big.   It's not enough and whether you want to admit it or not. It's still not enough.   "Enough for today" and "we will do more tomorrow" is a trap and before you know it ten years have passed with little or nothing to show for it because you tricked yourself into false progress.   You must push more. Every time.   No matter.how.much you want to stop. No matter how much you want to say "I've done well" "I've done enough" you need to do more. You need to go outside.   Mark is right. And I think people are underestimating what mark has dealt with because he always has a smile on his face.   The best entertainers are typically very mentally unwell.

This really is what it‚Äôs like, almost every day. It‚Äôs hard, everything is hard, even when you try, you tire so quickly and want to give up. It‚Äôs so easy to give up, and it really feels like pushing past the fatigue is an impassible wall.  That voice, speaking familiarly, there‚Äôs no reason to argue with it‚Äîyou‚Äôve been listening to it for so long that you don‚Äôt accept anything different. ‚ÄúYou‚Äôre stupid‚Äù, I know, ‚Äúyou failed‚Äù, like usual, ‚Äúthis is a waste‚Äù, isn‚Äôt it always? There‚Äôs safety in the negativity. As long as you listen to it, you have endless excuses for everything and no reason to accept when you do things right that it has something to do with you. The success was exterior finalised, not because of anything you did. And from there, the cycle is endless. It feels so hopeless, like there‚Äôs no way out. ‚ÄúThis is where you belong, because you‚Äôre not a good person‚Äù, what makes you a bad person? ‚ÄúEverything‚Äù, define everything? ‚ÄúEverything you‚Äôve done wrong‚Äù, but what if the bad result of X event had nothing to do with anything you did? ‚ÄúIt went poorly because it was you, as opposed to someone else.‚Äù And thus cycling back to being a bad person who doesn‚Äôt deserve happiness and never succeeds. If you accept your successes, you have to, in some forms, accept that some of those negative beliefs you have aren‚Äôt true. But that doesn‚Äôt make sense, because you‚Äôre a bad person?   It‚Äôs very difficult to escape from. This game points everything out and really shows what it‚Äôs like. It feels nice to see Mark fighting the narrative‚ÄîI hope to be that strong one day.  Thanks for playing this, Mark.

Interesting fact: In some countries "First floor" doesn't refer to the ground floor but to the floor above it.

It seems mathematically sound to me to call the ground floor the 1st floor. During your first hour of work, you have been working 0 hours. Only when you reach your 2nd hour of work have you been working for 1 hour. Most programming functions also index from 0 in this fashion. 1st element = index 0, 2nd element = index 1. Naming the floors of a building in the US follows this same logic: 1st Floor = index 0, 2nd Floor = index 1.   When I saw the English translation in the video, and the mentioning of "first floor" from a non-US person, I figured Mark would run into this problem. It's mostly only a few older buildings in the US that still use the G +1 convention. I'm mainly against G + 1 and prefer 1st + 2nd, but other things from outside the US, I have no problem adopting, like metric which is much easier to use than imperial in everyone's mostly-decimal systems.

Pharmacy technician here: prior authorization are a huge pain. The insurance company doesn't want to pay for the drug so the doctor has to contact them to be yeah idiots, I wrote the prescription because I want them to have it. Also, they SHOULD have ordered it. I worked for CVS and I couldn't stand the lack of patient care we were limited to. We had to get permission to order these newer medications from our manager. If the manager didn't think it was worth it to order the medications, us technicians were prohibited from ordering it.

One of my jobs in Dr office I work for is doing prior authorizations for certain medications the dr writes out. I hate having to deal with insurance companies and their processes when it comes to that. I work for a rheumatologist, so some of the meds he has people on, are for auto immune diseases or things to help slow process of rheumatoid. Alot of our patients are elderly and have been on some of these medications for years. It is always a hassle with insurance companies telling us they don't think a certain medication is medically necessary.

At least it's "just" ADHD meds. My husband had this issue in Australia with epilepsy meds a few years ago, he had to go to his neurology hospital every time he needed a new pack, no other pharmacy carried it because it was relatively new and the community demand wasn't there yet. (But they could special order in Sodium Valproate monthly when he was on that.)

The sad part of the idea for [Redacted] is that the number of people who truly experienced it can now ever only decrease.   The most irretrievable, sad and non-transferrable part is that missing feeling of it being "alive" and "official", of having the liberty to go straight to the channel and see all the vids there and knowing that there would be a new one tomorrow, of living the countdown in real time, feeling its weight and having the comment sections and other social media pages (like the reddit page) to interact with the thriving community who was feeling that weight along with you rather than sadly and nostalgically talking in the past tense about it. Seeing how different people reacted to the incoming demise, from sadness to outright denial was a big part of it too.   You can look at the memories others have captured but the soul is gone forever, which is a really cool and unique part of the channel. You can probably find that final live stream but the timer won't truly mean anything to you, nor will the end pushing of the delete button since the result of that button being pushed is the only experience you have ever had with the remaining scraps of content left behind and salvaged. Looking back to before the end can and never will be the same as looking forward towards the end and living in the moment.  At some stage, there will only be one person in the entire world who, now a pensioner in their early nineties, will be sitting and reminiscing about two lovable idiots with a deleted Youtube channel. The only one left who once watched them tear phone books, hold viking funerals, sing disclaimer songs, do the dance of Italy, forget the name of a skillet, play nutball, build a dog house, wax each other suggestively, mix pancake batter with a "rubber love sausage", goof around in escape rooms and experience ethical dilemas together.   I kinda feel bad for whichever one of us that person will be because they will have absolutely no-one who shares these memories with them and truly appreciates the community that once existed there.   (Some cynics will probably bash me a bit for being this dramatic, since "its only a YouTube channel". But you know what, as someone who does English Literature in 17-18 education, if I'm not going to be overly wishy-washy about it then who will, damn it?)
Holy shit, I want you to write my eulogy. That was an amazing way to describe the utter sadness of it all.

As much as I miss it, the feeling of being able to say ‚ÄúYeah I was there, I experienced this‚Äù makes me very happy.

im about two months late to the funeral service, however im going to be dramatic and say what i need to say.  unus annus was a memory that can only truly be understood by those who were counting down the days in present time. of course, there are probably ways to find both the end live stream as well as the videos from the channel itself, but watching them after the core of the project has already vanished is entirely different than experiencing it first hand. the relationship that every one of us fans developed with the channel was each different, taking into account both when we found it and how many videos we got to watch. as one of those who found the channel a few days post-creation, i grew a deep emotional connection with it very quickly. i remember each personal countdown milestone (300 days, 200 days, 150, 100, 50, it goes on) hit me with a wave of preemptive nostalgia. even over a year later, im still unable to describe the sadness i felt both when the channel reached it's 7 day countdown, and the final 12 hours.  its time for a personal story of mine to top off the sundae of nostalgia and "homesickness" i get from reminiscing on unus annus. for a bit of background, im very adamant about giving a person, or group of people, my full attention when talking to or hanging out with them. im not a very confrontational person and i also struggle with eye contact, but i also do my best not to be preoccupied when talking to or being around others.  on november 14th, 2020, i had the opportunity to go to the mall with a few of my friends that i hadn't seen since covid/quarantine started. of course, i said yes to their invite and was very excited to see them--that was, until i remembered that november 14th was the final day of unus annus. i debated cancelling my plans with these friends (yes, it meant that much to me), however i soon realized how inconsiderate, and frankly, self centered, it would be of me. so, i opted to still go to the mall with these friends on that day. when we got there, we stopped at the food court first to get, well, food, and while we were waiting for one of my friend's orders to be ready, i got the notification on my phone that unus annus was live. i briefly hesitated, but refused to miss the livestream, and so i opened it. one of the friends with me knew of unus annus and had watched a few videos, but wasn't even close to as attached as i was/still am. while my friends finished their food, i watched the livestream and tried my very best not to cry in the middle of our local mall (spoiler alert: i ended up failing. yes, i cried).  as we were getting ready to start walking around, and doing what we were there to do--shop, and have fun--i continued watching the livestream. this was the first time that i had been more focused on anything than my friends while hanging out with them. they were concerned, but let me be. (one of my friends has a video of us walking through the mall as a small group, since there was 6 of us, myself included. every time i see this video i cant help but laugh, because im in the back of the group/video with my face completely glued to my phone).  the entire time my friends and i were in the mall, i watched the livestream. afterwards, we all planned to go out for dinner, and we did. i chose to stay in the car and watch the livestream. that night, they all received a video of me on snapchat completely bawling my eyes out over the deletion of the channel. my cry count, if i remember correctly, was 18.  yes, this was long and dramatic, but it feels fitting.  memento mori, unus annus.

During night Bigfoot gets a bonus to attack, in the day he gets a bonus to healing. Turning off your lights actually makes you harder to see. Smells and noise attracts him more than you realize. He can literally see the direction of a sound from half way across the map! The thumping is him weakening trees and gathering weapons. If you stay quiet you can hear what sounds like rope twisting, that means a tree trap is near by. It is better to place those hazards at his feet and shoot them, than it is to try to hit him with it or detonate (gas cans, generators, dynamite, etc.) Before you trek a long distance, wait for day light. The map is randomly generated. It uses the same land mass but locations get randomly placed for each new game. His hideout is at the marble caves.

The sad big head in happy smile head land is the only truly sad and vulnerable, taking the injustice out on all of the "happy normal people". But the kid, now with his happy mask broken, is able to console the big head after it's thrown through an emotional rollercoaster.  Maybe the kid has witnessed the harshness of reality, felt scorned by society at large. Internalizing this idea of everyone living a false, lunatic happiness. Where everything bad is good, and just being himself makes him a target to more suffering.

holy shit rewatching this after knowing what it's about makes so much sense. the rest of this comment is pretty long as it's my theory of the game so if you're not interested you can scroll past   the game is divided into three parts. (spoiler warning if anybody here hasn't seen the full game) the first part is the child's initial trauma. the many depictions of toys represent the childhood joys, and the inevitable corruption in all of the toys is the result of some external factor destroying the comforts of a healthy and happy childhood. the ball that the child chases after represents that external factor. it appears to be leading the child somewhere and being playful along the way. the ball is tricking the child into going down a dangerous path by showing the child fun adventures and making the child forget the corruption of the adventures. when the child falls down into that pit of spikes, the ball is what leads the child there. i think the spikes might actually be needles, referencing the game's theme of drug addiction. the second part of the game is much happier, full of color. this part is the beginning of the addiction. the child has found a way to cope with the initial trauma and appears calmer, much less scared. for those on the outside who can see the child, the world the child is in seems unsafe and unnatural, but for the child, it is comforting and secure. the circular shape of the world represents the neverending cycle that comes with any addiction. it later progresses into a much more dangerous environment with oversaturated colors, representing the effects of the addiction. the third part of the game is very unsettling, full of broken happy faces. this is the spiral that happens as a result of the addiction. everything seems like it should be happy and fun, but in reality it is terrifying and destructive. the child can't fight the addiction because of the initial trauma. the child wasn't taught how to find healthy coping mechanisms and so it is impossible to break free from the cycle. the mix of vibrant colors with muted grays represents the trauma that comes with addiction.  this is just my theory, and I'm sure there are a thousand more out there, but I had fun looking over this game. it's a super interesting way to portray drug abuse and it helps the audience to understand it a lot better. also the visuals, while creepy, are super fucking cool.

The fear and hesitation that follows alongside the first voyage of any ship; spacefaring or seafaring, is immense. The anxiety brought upon by the induced paranoia of unpreparedness is something that follows every member of a crew. The chance that the ship springs a leak and begins to sink, the off-chance that something big attacks the ship...mutiny, sea/space sickness, and the ever developing fear of being lost in a place you yourself are not familiar with.  Fear itself is a powerful tool in the hands of no one.  And what it inspires in people whosoever's hearts are either hardened or weakened, is something terrible indeed. This preview shows that example very well, as the chaos of multiple intervening voices becoming more and more panicked show that very same growing anxiety. Doubt sets in, and everything comes to the Captain of the vessel to bring things to a head. To bring together the crew that until that point, had been teetering at the edge of tearing themselves apart.  And though they might succeed in their journey, they will not arrive at their destination without taking with them the fear, and memory of those who died along the way.  "O' Captain, My Captain", indeed.

The issue is that it's become more and more acceptable over time for developers to pump out games in an Incomplete state rather than take the time to make sure they're functioning properly. Map bugs and texture issues are ignorable, but having one of the main threats in the game literally ignore the only method you have of escaping it due to an A.I./Pathing Bug is an entirely inexcusable issue that never should occur. It completely ruins immersion, can cause you to lose literal hours of progress, and is a cheap attempt to artificially inflate difficulty if done purposefully, and straight up negligent if done unintentionally. Saying "it's no big deal they'll fix it later" is a disservice to the people who paid money for the game before they fixed it

2:39 For those curious, Mark is referring to Chekhov's Gun, a dramatic principle which states that if you show or state something interesting or dramatic you should show some sort of payoff for it later on. The example often used and where the principle gets it's namesake is that if you show a gun on a wall in the first season you should show it being used in the third season

As much as I think FNAF: SB is cool, I still believe Scott Cawthon should have stopped this series at the 3rd or 4th game. He had the ability to do so, as each game gave him a good ending to end upon. I still enjoy the games, but I believe that this "Cash Cow" has been milked dry. Another good place that Cawthon could have ended on was the Ultimate Custom Night. UCN had the potential to be the perfect ending point: the Purple Guy is in hell and paying for his crimes forever. But, no, the money was too good and the fans wanted more. Think about it, after this installment in the series, how much further can this rabbit hole go? Freddy was right when he said "It's time to end this." in the fire ending of this game. Don't get me wrong, I still enjoy the games, but I believe it would have been better to stop the series sooner.

you know what maybe would have been good with this game? actually having it be in the dark with just a flashlight, or even a found footage style game with night vision! no neon lights, the occasional staff bot patrolling where it makes sense, and having the animatronics actually be a proper threat. having fun, friendly freddy is nice, but it takes away from the fact this is meant to be a horror game. like, sure - have the lights be on at the beginning, because it's 15 minutes till closing and that makes sense - but a sudden power outage as the place shuts down for the night, would have such an eerie feeling. no neon lights or an army of staff bots patrolling because it wouldn't make sense to have so many in one place. have the elevator working but be dimly lit, maybe the music could genuinely slowly get corrupted during the night too?  you could keep fun friendly freddy but have him slowly corrupt during the night because of a virus, or smth. the darkness throughout would make little things like the animatronic in the slide tunnel or the bots offering you the party passes have more scare-factor... like they're startling, of course, but imagine being in the darkness, shining a flashlight down the tunnel and suddenly the animatronic pops out, disfigured and shouting about a security breach. also, have sun/moon be more of a threat! hell, give us information on why gregory is in the building! idk, these are all probably dumb ideas and just little things i thought about after watching this playthrough and reading the comments, but i'm just spitballing here.
